WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.720
Thank you everyone for coming. I'm really excited to follow up on the spotlight video we saw

00:00:06.720 --> 00:00:12.720
yesterday morning where we got to see Pierce's story and his battle against blood cancer.

00:00:13.600 --> 00:00:20.559
And so every year there are tens of thousands of patients like Pierce where their best hope

00:00:20.559 --> 00:00:26.400
for a cure is often through an unrelated donor transplant who at that point in time is basically

00:00:26.400 --> 00:00:35.119
a total stranger. And so it is our job as data scientists to use our data superpowers to help

00:00:35.119 --> 00:00:42.639
identify these donors to better serve patients like Pierce. But one of the challenges that I

00:00:42.639 --> 00:00:49.279
find data science typically get themselves into is how do we get these insights into production

00:00:49.919 --> 00:00:54.240
into the hands of decision makers, in our case physicians who are selecting donors,

00:00:55.200 --> 00:01:00.639
and how do we get the insights to them when they need them. And so over a couple of years we've

00:01:00.639 --> 00:01:05.440
had a journey of trying to really make this process much easier and reduce the friction

00:01:05.440 --> 00:01:12.480
between local development and production environments. And so it all starts around

00:01:12.480 --> 00:01:17.519
five years ago we were a young data team where we were doing lots of ad hoc analyses in R.

00:01:18.400 --> 00:01:22.480
And it was kind of a cautionary tale of be careful what you wish for because we did a

00:01:22.480 --> 00:01:27.680
lot of great analyses. They were so great that stakeholders wanted them refreshed every morning.

00:01:27.680 --> 00:01:33.440
So I would set an 8 o'clock alarm, run a series of 20 reports, make sure everything's working,

00:01:34.160 --> 00:01:40.320
and rinse and repeat. And so that got very, very tedious and so as one did back in the day

00:01:40.959 --> 00:01:46.720
we were feeling lucky and we searched the web for how can we automate the running of these R scripts.

00:01:47.680 --> 00:01:54.559
And the first result was Windows task scheduler. And it actually made a lot of sense conceptually,

00:01:54.559 --> 00:02:00.720
so it replaced me and my alarm clock with a Windows server managed by our IT department

00:02:00.720 --> 00:02:07.839
running on a task scheduler. But it had quite a few pain points, one being we didn't always know

00:02:07.839 --> 00:02:14.080
when reports failed, which is a big problem to have. And as we started having more and more

00:02:14.240 --> 00:02:21.279
infrastructure and reports on this server, syncing files became quite difficult. So pushing from our

00:02:21.279 --> 00:02:26.960
laptops to our Git repository is straightforward, but then we had to build out a whole process on

00:02:26.960 --> 00:02:32.880
the Windows task scheduler service to sync with Git and inevitably there are fire drills where

00:02:32.880 --> 00:02:37.679
people are hot fixing on the server itself. You have to go the other direction, which is quite

00:02:37.679 --> 00:02:44.559
a pain to manage. And so we were wondering that there's got to be a better way to do this, right?

00:02:45.279 --> 00:02:51.759
And so that's when we realized we reinvented the wheel, only our wheel was a little bit more

00:02:51.759 --> 00:03:00.720
squarish than we would have liked, whereas software like PositConnect just works plug and play

00:03:00.720 --> 00:03:07.759
and you get high-quality enterprise-grade software. And so part of the reason why I'm

00:03:07.759 --> 00:03:14.479
giving this talk is because even in 2025 with AI, the very first result for our automation

00:03:14.479 --> 00:03:21.679
is still Windows task scheduler, and so this is my contribution to fight back against their monopoly

00:03:21.679 --> 00:03:30.399
on our automation. So why does my team love PositConnect? The first thing that we like

00:03:30.399 --> 00:03:34.639
is that scheduling and monitoring just comes out of the box. We don't have to worry about that.

00:03:35.360 --> 00:03:41.119
So no more waking up early and running reports by hand, and more importantly, we can have

00:03:41.119 --> 00:03:46.559
proactive alerting. So we built on top of the PositConnect API to have this automation status

00:03:46.559 --> 00:03:54.720
report, which summarizes every single day our entire catalog of reports and finds out how many

00:03:54.720 --> 00:04:00.000
ones failed and there's even conditional logic to alert certain people if certain reports failed.

00:04:01.360 --> 00:04:07.440
Secondly, and I think this is my favorite aspect, is that we don't have to change how we work.

00:04:08.240 --> 00:04:14.800
So we can develop in our favorite ID of choice, whether that's RStudio, VS Code, or Positron,

00:04:15.520 --> 00:04:20.160
as long as we all agree to push back to our Git repository at least once in a while.

00:04:22.239 --> 00:04:27.839
And we get to use our favorite code-first tools like R and Python, Shiny applications,

00:04:27.839 --> 00:04:33.920
Jupyter Notebooks, Quartel, just to name a few. And to really appreciate why this is such a good

00:04:33.920 --> 00:04:38.959
benefit to have, I think it's insightful to compare to alternative approaches to how you

00:04:38.959 --> 00:04:44.000
might deploy something in production. So a very common framework is to use Docker containers,

00:04:44.640 --> 00:04:49.600
and they are a way to package all your code and application into this one container, which

00:04:49.600 --> 00:04:55.359
you can ship anywhere and run anywhere in theory. But in practice, one, there's a big learning

00:04:55.359 --> 00:05:00.640
curve. So if you understand everything in this Docker file, props to you. But again, we're trying

00:05:00.640 --> 00:05:06.000
to make the friction as low as possible from local development to insight and production.

00:05:06.959 --> 00:05:12.559
And Docker in particular, it's hard to inspect inside the container unless you really know how

00:05:12.559 --> 00:05:20.399
to probe around in there, and it can be quite a learning curve. A second approach is maybe you

00:05:20.399 --> 00:05:26.880
want to try some cloud infrastructure, like serverless AWS Lambda functions. And again,

00:05:26.880 --> 00:05:31.119
they have their time and place, but when you're talking about reducing friction from local code

00:05:31.119 --> 00:05:35.920
to production code, Lambda functions have to be structured in a particular way. They all have this

00:05:35.920 --> 00:05:41.839
handler function, which takes in two arguments, event and context, and those are runtime-dependent.

00:05:41.839 --> 00:05:46.880
So wherever it's running in production, those are events that are coming in, and so it's a little

00:05:46.880 --> 00:05:51.760
bit hard to mock up your local environment to have exactly those events in context. Of course,

00:05:51.760 --> 00:05:57.519
you can do it, but then you're increasing the differences between your development code locally

00:05:57.519 --> 00:06:06.160
and your production code deployed into AWS. And so a third benefit of PositConnect is actually

00:06:06.160 --> 00:06:12.000
something we didn't even ask for or didn't realize we really enjoyed until we saw that it actually

00:06:12.079 --> 00:06:18.799
gives you an entire user interface to show your reports. So we've been thinking entirely so far

00:06:18.799 --> 00:06:24.880
based on scheduling, automating compute somewhere else off my laptop. But it turns out it's really

00:06:24.880 --> 00:06:30.399
nice when you can automate that compute and also show at the same time a really high-quality

00:06:31.519 --> 00:06:36.640
report. So in this case, we have a screenshot of our data science storefront, which is a

00:06:36.640 --> 00:06:41.679
portal document that is able to, it's kind of like a meta report that highlights all the other

00:06:41.679 --> 00:06:48.000
content that we want to highlight, and we can build a whole bunch of dashboards, shiny applications

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:56.320
for people to use right within the same tool. Okay. So those are some reasons that we really

00:06:56.320 --> 00:07:02.959
enjoy PositConnect, but how does it fit into our architecture or more generally the data science

00:07:02.959 --> 00:07:09.440
lifecycle? And so this is probably not a surprise, but it almost always starts with an idea or

00:07:09.440 --> 00:07:14.559
problem that you're trying to solve. And so for us, that was trying to predict the likelihood that a

00:07:14.559 --> 00:07:21.519
donor is willing and able to donate. And we call that the donor readiness score. And so once we

00:07:21.519 --> 00:07:28.160
have that idea, then we do what we do best as data scientists. We do some exploration, exploratory

00:07:28.160 --> 00:07:33.600
data analysis locally, we train a model, we run some validation, make sure that the model is

00:07:33.600 --> 00:07:41.200
performing as we would expect, and we do it with our favorite IDs of choice. But once we start

00:07:41.200 --> 00:07:47.920
getting to the step where we have code that looks like, take our model, take some new data,

00:07:47.920 --> 00:07:52.160
calculate some new predictions, this is when you want to start thinking about deploying to

00:07:52.160 --> 00:07:57.200
production so you don't have to run this four times a day every single day for a long time.

00:07:58.399 --> 00:08:05.519
And that's where PositConnect fits in for our architecture. So it's hooked up to our GitLab

00:08:05.519 --> 00:08:12.079
repository through a Git integration. And this is a one-time setup that basically gives the PositConnect

00:08:12.079 --> 00:08:19.679
server read access to everything that we push to Git. And so things like our data science storefront,

00:08:19.679 --> 00:08:27.200
it's a portal document in our GitLab repository, and PositConnect has access to that along with

00:08:28.160 --> 00:08:32.880
the usual open-source packages. And the one change you have to make to your workflow using

00:08:32.880 --> 00:08:39.520
PositConnect, unlike Docker or Lambdas, is you just have to create this one manifest.json file,

00:08:39.520 --> 00:08:42.799
and you can do that automatically through one of these two commands, depending on if you're

00:08:42.799 --> 00:08:49.119
using Python or R, and the manifest is basically an instruction manual for the server to know what

00:08:49.119 --> 00:08:53.119
version of Python or R you're using, what packages you're using, and their versions,

00:08:53.119 --> 00:08:59.679
so it can help set up that environment. And once you have that manifest.json file,

00:08:59.679 --> 00:09:06.559
you go to the PositConnect UI, you find the file or the folder where the manifest is in,

00:09:06.559 --> 00:09:11.440
you click the blue button to deploy your content, and then you have your awesome report that you can

00:09:11.440 --> 00:09:19.119
link to and share right away. And it's really helpful for maintenance, too, because PositConnect

00:09:19.119 --> 00:09:23.440
automatically checks all your content with a manifest every 15 minutes to see if there's

00:09:23.440 --> 00:09:29.119
updates, so we don't have to implement any extra CICD on our end to make sure that the changes we

00:09:29.119 --> 00:09:34.320
pushed gets reflected to the latest version of the report. That's all done under the hood,

00:09:34.320 --> 00:09:43.359
all that complexity is abstracted away. So the next critical piece to have in our architecture

00:09:44.159 --> 00:09:50.719
is introducing our database, because you can work with CSVs locally, you can work with pins for a

00:09:50.719 --> 00:09:56.640
time, but you always want to connect to your database because you want to have a live connection

00:09:56.640 --> 00:10:03.599
in production. So let's zoom in there a little bit. So the database set up to PositConnect is,

00:10:03.599 --> 00:10:08.960
again, a one-time connection, and there are Posit professional drivers that are included

00:10:08.960 --> 00:10:15.760
that support most common databases, around 15 the last time I checked. And once you have this

00:10:15.760 --> 00:10:19.520
two-way connection where you can read data from Snowflake and also write back to data

00:10:20.159 --> 00:10:24.559
to Snowflake, you can do things like score millions of records per day,

00:10:26.080 --> 00:10:33.599
and schedule this to run as much as you need. And one kind of interesting use case that we

00:10:33.599 --> 00:10:40.479
would recommend for your database of choice is to be able to leverage that database compute when

00:10:40.479 --> 00:10:45.679
you need to for the occasional job that doesn't fit into memory in your PositConnect server.

00:10:46.559 --> 00:10:52.000
And databases are a great place to do that because they're used to dealing with big data all the time

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:55.679
and your data already lives there, so your security department's going to be really,

00:10:55.679 --> 00:11:01.440
really happy that there's one less transfer of data moving around. And for us, we use Snowflake

00:11:01.440 --> 00:11:07.039
and there's Snowpark functionality, so we can actually write Python user-defined functions

00:11:07.039 --> 00:11:13.119
that run natively in the warehouse. So when we have to occasionally do a huge compute job,

00:11:13.119 --> 00:11:19.200
we just scale up the warehouse, use some Python, and there you go. You can get more creative for

00:11:19.200 --> 00:11:24.640
other databases that don't support Python or Python-like languages by, you know, converting

00:11:24.640 --> 00:11:31.359
your model objects into SQL. If you're interested in that, you can look into Orbital, but there's

00:11:31.359 --> 00:11:37.359
creative ways to leverage your warehouse compute when your server isn't doing the job for you.

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:45.440
Okay, so I think these are kind of the key components to these production workflows that

00:11:45.440 --> 00:11:50.000
are not too different from your local development, and I think this is a great place to start.

00:11:51.119 --> 00:11:57.679
But once you have maybe 10 or a lot of content onto PositConnect, you might start realizing that

00:11:57.679 --> 00:12:02.400
you're actually copy-pasting a lot of code, like when you connect to your database, it's the same

00:12:02.400 --> 00:12:08.719
20 lines of boilerplate code. And so here's a good opportunity to think about using internal

00:12:08.719 --> 00:12:16.799
packages. And we personally use Posit Package Manager for two main reasons. One, it automatically

00:12:16.799 --> 00:12:23.200
builds new package versions as long as you push to Git. So again, we don't have to do any CICD

00:12:23.200 --> 00:12:30.239
to update the package versions. That complexity is all abstracted away from us. And from a user

00:12:30.239 --> 00:12:35.919
perspective, it's also super nice to just use the same commands that you would to install any

00:12:35.919 --> 00:12:40.960
other package, even though they are completely internal, completely custom-made. You can install

00:12:40.960 --> 00:12:46.400
a package to install a package from Git for you, or you can just, you know, use the same commands

00:12:46.400 --> 00:12:49.760
that you normally would to install these packages. So that's really, really helpful.

00:12:52.880 --> 00:12:58.239
Okay. And there's one more piece of the diagram that is missing, and it's going to be a little

00:12:58.239 --> 00:13:05.119
bit dependent to each of your specific use cases and organizations. But basically the question of,

00:13:06.719 --> 00:13:10.719
you know, when we talk about data and machine learning, our models are only as good as the

00:13:10.719 --> 00:13:16.400
data that comes in. And also, if no one has access to our models, then they're really not

00:13:16.400 --> 00:13:23.359
useful at all. So how do you connect data in a holistic way? And the general advice that I would

00:13:23.359 --> 00:13:30.000
have is to try to keep everything within one central database as much as possible. And so,

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:36.239
for example, we have a lot of input data, for example, from our donor registry. We have a lot

00:13:36.239 --> 00:13:42.400
of other sources of data, but we try to make sure that everything eventually flows into Snowflake,

00:13:42.400 --> 00:13:48.159
our central database, somehow. And we also work closely with our engineering and integration

00:13:48.159 --> 00:13:53.599
teams to make sure that there's a pathway for data that we send back to Snowflake to connect

00:13:53.599 --> 00:13:59.840
to downstream applications. So for us, our physicians use an application called MatchSource

00:13:59.840 --> 00:14:04.880
that we built in-house, which is what they use to select donors for their patients.

00:14:05.840 --> 00:14:13.200
And so, having a process where all the data that we're producing ends up in Snowflake,

00:14:13.200 --> 00:14:23.440
and that has a clear path to application. And so, with that, we're able to put all the pieces

00:14:23.440 --> 00:14:29.119
together to create this, you know, architecture diagram that we use for data science that really

00:14:29.119 --> 00:14:35.039
focuses on development experience for the data scientist, so that we can bring all our awesome

00:14:35.039 --> 00:14:41.039
insights that we develop locally and have a really clean process to push them into production,

00:14:41.679 --> 00:14:48.000
but also without compromising or missing features. And we're able to, you know,

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:54.000
generate useful insights that people can use, and that's running not on our laptops,

00:14:54.000 --> 00:15:00.880
and it's running in an automated fashion. And so, with that, I'm happy to take a couple

00:15:00.880 --> 00:15:06.559
questions. You can read more about the slides or more about what we do in these links,

00:15:06.559 --> 00:15:09.440
and I'm always happy to connect and chat more. So, thank you.

00:15:16.159 --> 00:15:23.119
All right. Thank you, Adam. We have time for a few questions. So, the first question for you.

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:31.200
Could you elaborate more on Git-backed pushing to PositConnect? Does the report or app update on

00:15:31.200 --> 00:15:40.640
commit? Yes. So, the short answer is that yes. It basically updates on commit to the branch

00:15:41.599 --> 00:15:46.880
within 15 minutes. And so, you can think about PositConnect is running every 15 minutes,

00:15:46.880 --> 00:15:51.200
checking to see if there's been changes to any piece of content you have on the server.

00:15:51.760 --> 00:15:56.239
And if it picks up any new changes, it's going to fold those in and automatically deploy a new

00:15:56.239 --> 00:16:01.039
version without you having to go in and click buttons yourself. If you want it to be immediate,

00:16:01.039 --> 00:16:06.400
you can go in and click a button to do it faster, but otherwise, we generally have a workflow of

00:16:06.400 --> 00:16:11.119
push to Git, merge, check our changes, and once they're merged into the main branch,

00:16:11.119 --> 00:16:18.479
then we know it'll update in PositConnect. Okay. Another question. What features are

00:16:18.479 --> 00:16:24.799
missing from PositConnect? So, I have one nitpicking one that comes to mind.

00:16:27.599 --> 00:16:32.799
So, when you schedule reports on PositConnect, there's the common use cases of every day or

00:16:32.799 --> 00:16:37.039
every month or every 15th of the month. But sometimes we get weird requests from people

00:16:37.039 --> 00:16:42.799
that are like, can you run this on the 19th business day of this month or at least four

00:16:42.799 --> 00:16:49.760
times of the day that aren't nicely every hour or some periodic interval. And so, there's ways

00:16:49.760 --> 00:16:54.159
to work around doing that by making a parameterized report, but it would be nice if you could just

00:16:54.159 --> 00:16:58.880
point and click and be like, this is the schedule that I want. But that's kind of a nitpicking.

00:16:59.599 --> 00:17:06.239
Broader, I'll have to think about that. Connect with me and we'll talk more. I'll try to think

00:17:06.239 --> 00:17:12.079
of something. Okay. That's all the questions. Thank you so much. Adam, another round of applause,

00:17:12.079 --> 00:17:17.599
please.

